Market Based Rate Tariff 1. Availability: Mordor ES1 LLC (Seller) makes electric energy and capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. Seller also makes available to any purchaser the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph 1: Ancillary Services a) MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. b) PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. c) NYISO: The seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System, Operator, Inc. (NYISO). d) ISO-NE: The seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. e) CAISO: The seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. f) SPP: The seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g) Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission providers OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity, and ancillary services by Seller, which are (a) subject to the jurisdiction of the Commission, and (b) not made pursuant to another tariff on file with the Commission. 3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and the Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Sellers market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Sellers market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the appliable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Sellers market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: The Commission granted Seller in Docket No. ER24-___-000 the following waivers and blanket authorization: (i) waiver of Part 41 of the Commissions regulations regarding accounts, records, and memoranda; (ii) waiver of Part 101 of the Commissions regulations regarding the Commissions Uniform System of Accounts, with the exception of provisions thereof that apply to hydropower licensees with respect to licensed hydropower projects; (iii) Waiver of Part 141 of the Commissions regulations regarding statements and reports, except Section 141.15; (iv) Blanket approval under Part 34 for all future issuances of securities and assumptions of liability; and (v) Waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commissions regulations, except Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16. 7. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Southwest Region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), and a Category 1 Seller in all other regions. 8. Effective Date. This Tariff is effective on and after the date on which the Commission permits it to become effective.

CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
THIS CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this Agreement) is entered into and effective as of February 13, 2024 (the Effective Date), by and among Mordor ES1 LLC, a Delaware limited liability company as a Co-Tenant (as defined below) (Mordor ES1) and Coso Finance Partners, a California general partnership as a Co-Tenant (as defined below) (CFP), CFP in its role as the initial Manager (as defined below) (Mordor ES1, CFP, and the Manager are each referred to herein individually as a Party, and collectively as the Parties).
RECITALS:
A. The United States of America, represented by various contracting officers previously entered into a certain contract, Contract No. N68711-05-C-0001 (the Navy Contract) with China Lake Joint Venture (CLJV). Pursuant to the Navy Contract, Navy granted to CLJV, among other rights, the right to develop electric power from the geothermal resources on public lands located in China Lake, California. CLJV subsequently transferred certain rights with respect to the Navy Contract and, as of 2007, all rights, titles, interests and obligation under the Navy Contract relevant to this Agreement were consolidated in the Coso Geothermal Contract Trust, a Delaware statutory trust (Contract Trust). On February 16, 2017, Contract Trust granted to Coso Geothermal Power Holdings, LLC (CGPH) all of Contract Trusts rights, title and interest and to perform all Contract Trusts obligations under the Navy Contract and to CFP the right to use all of Contract Trusts rights and power necessary to retain ownership of or otherwise relate to the Transmission Line (as described below).
B. CGPH currently owns and operates that certain Navy I geothermal power facility located on the Naval Weapons Center in China Lake, California with a combined nameplate capacity of approximately 80 net MW operated subject to the Navy Contract (the Existing Project).
C. Mordor ES1 is developing and will own and operate a 25 MW battery energy storage project, as further described on Exhibit A attached hereto (the Battery Storage Project), that will be located in the vicinity of a portion of the Existing Project on property known as BLM West leased from the U.S. Bureau of Land Management (BLM) pursuant to the BLM Lease and BLM 25690 Site License (each as defined below).
D. In connection with the Existing Project, CFP owns and operates that certain approximately 29- mile 115 Kv transmission line, together with all associated permits and other authorizations necessary and appropriate to operate and maintain the transmission line, as further described in Exhibit B attached hereto (the Transmission Line) through which electricity produced by the Existing Project is transmitted for delivery to the transmission system owned by Southern California Edison Company (SCE) and controlled by the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO).
E. Each of CFP, SCE and CAISO is a party to that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement, dated June 3, 2011 (as amended, restated or otherwise modified from time to time, an Interconnection Agreement) which is expected to be amended to provide Mordor
4 ES1 with the rights to use certain interconnection facilities described therein and the right to interconnect the Battery Storage Project to the electric transmission owned by SCE and under the control of CAISO.
F. All rights and obligations with respect to the Transmission Line are referred to herein as the Shared Facilities.
G. Mordor ES1 and CFP will share in obligations relating to, and certain costs of, the Shared Facilities in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement.
H. Mordor ES1 and CFP also wish to appoint CFP as the Manager for the provision of certain services with respect to the Shared Facilities at such time and on the terms and conditions contained herein. The Manager obtains service through that certain Operations and Maintenance Agreement, dated as of August 17, 2017 (together with any replacement thereof, O&M Agreement), between Managers affiliates, CGPH, Coso Transmission Line Partners, Coso Energy Developers, Coso Power Developers, and Coso Operating Company LLC (together with any assignee, successor or replacement thereof, Operator) under which Operator provides services necessary for Manager to perform its obligations as Manager hereunder.

Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible, from and after the Closing in proportion to its relative Percentage Interest (unless the Co-Tenants are disproportionately at fault with respect to the applicable Liabilities relating to or arising out of actions or events occurring from and after the Closing (and relating to or arising out of actions or events occurring prior to the
22 Closing, which shall be the sole responsibility of CFP), in which case responsibility shall be apportioned in proportion to each Co-Tenants relative fault), for all Liabilities related to any investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action or related activities with respect to such Shared Facilities.

6.12 Allocation of Line Losses and Capacity Reductions.
(a) On and after the Closing Date, line losses that occur over the Shared Facilities while both Projects are using the Shared Facilities to transmit energy shall be allocated as determined by CAISO.
(b) Any interruption, reduction in deliveries of, or other curtailment of electrical power through the Shared Facilities, or to the point of interconnection designated in the Interconnection Agreement, in each case instructed by the CAISO, shall be allocated to one or more Co-Tenants as CAISO shall determine and apportion to such Co-Tenants. If and only to the extent that CAISO does not determine and apportion such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power, the Manager shall, to the fullest extent possible allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to the Co-Tenant whose actions or inactions caused such interruption, reduction, or curtailment; provided, if and to the extent such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power cannot be attributed to the actions or inactions of any Co-Tenant, the Manager shall allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to each Co-Tenant in proportion to its respective Projects actual or scheduled output (in the case of the Battery Storage Project, its discharge output), if any, at the time of such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power (which shall be determined, to the extent applicable, based on the Projects respective output actually scheduled in the day-ahead or real-time market); provided further, if and to the extent such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power cannot be allocated in proportion to the respective Projects actual or scheduled output (such as when the Manager cannot reasonably determine what the output of either Project would have been during the duration of such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment had such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment had not occurred), the Manager shall allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to each Co-Tenant in proportion to its respective Projects Percentage Interest. To the extent that during such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power, either Co-Tenant is not using any portion or all of the capacity allocated to it under this Section 6.12(b), the Co-Tenants agree to reasonably cooperate to allow the other Co-Tenant to temporarily use such capacity not being used during such period of non-use. The foregoing provisions, however, do not apply to interruptions, reductions in deliveries or other curtailments attributed to (i) compliance with the applicable power purchase agreement or the failure of either Project to clear in any applicable CAISO market, (ii) dispatch down
25 instructions received by a Co-Tenant, or the Manager as the case may be, from the CAISO or SCE and directed at a Co-Tenants particular Project or (iii) reductions in the generation from the Existing Project necessary to accommodate the Battery Storage Projects rights under this Agreement. Actions taken by the Manager under this Section 6.12(b) shall be taken in a fair and neutral manner that does not disproportionately benefit or burden one Co-Tenant over another.
6.13 Withdrawal of a Co-Tenant.

At its election in its sole discretion, a Co-Tenant may relinquish its Undivided Interest and cease to be a Co-Tenant by delivery of a written notice (a Withdrawal Notice) to the other Co-Tenant and the Manager (and provide any notices required under the Interconnection Agreement) in which such Co-Tenant certifies, as of the date specified in the Withdrawal Notice (a Withdrawal Date), that it has obtained FERC approval (if, and to the extent necessary) under Section 203 of the Federal Power Act in connection with the grant, sale, transfer, assignment and conveyance of its Undivided Interest to the other Co-Tenant as contemplated in Section 6.13.2. Effective upon the Withdrawal Date and subject to the terms, conditions, restrictions and reservations set forth in this Agreement, (a) the withdrawing Co-Tenant shall, upon payment by the other Co-Tenant of the fair market value (as determined by an independent third party mutually acceptable to the Co-Tenants) of its Undivided Interest in and to the Shared Facilities, be deemed to have transferred to the other Co-Tenant its Undivided Interest in and to the Shared Facilities and (b) such Co-Tenant shall contemporaneously execute in recordable form, and deliver to the Manager for recording such documentation evidencing the termination, as applicable, of any easements or other property rights granted under this Agreement. Any such transfer shall be made AS IS, WITH ALL FAULTS AND WITHOUT (EXCEPT AS AND TO THE EXTENT OTHERWISE EXPRESSLY PROVIDED IN THIS AGREEMENT) ANY REPRESENTATIONS OR WARRANTIES WHATSOEVER, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, AND SPECIFICALLY EXCLUDING ANY WARRANTY OF TITLE, MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR ANY OTHER WARRANTY ARISING UNDER STATUTORY OR COMMON LAW. Notwithstanding the foregoing, no such transfer shall relieve the withdrawing Co-Tenant of any Liability that it has incurred prior to the Withdrawal Date.

Without limiting the provisions of Section 6.13.2, effective upon the Withdrawal Date, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the withdrawing Co-Tenant shall, without additional compensation, either release, assign or terminate its rights in the Shared Facilities, as may be requested by the remaining Co-Tenant in writing; provided, however, that no such release, assignment or termination shall be permitted to be undertaken in any manner that would materially and adversely affect the remaining Co-Tenants Project Specific Assets or the Shared Facilities.
6.13.4. Withdrawing Co-Tenants Remaining Rights and Obligations Under Agreement. After its Withdrawal Date, the withdrawing Co-Tenant shall remain a party to this Agreement but shall have no rights or obligations under this Agreement except those set forth in
26 Section 4.1, Section 4.2 and Section 4.3 (in each case, relating to the payment of its Percentage Interest (prior to the Withdrawal Date) of (x) Shared Expenses incurred prior to the Withdrawal Date and (y) Removal Costs, as reasonably projected by the Manager), Section 5.3, Article 10 and Article 12. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, no withdrawal of a Co-Tenant shall relieve such Co-Tenant of any Liability accruing or arising prior to the date on which such Co-Tenant ceases to serve as a Co-Tenant.

All reasonable costs and expenses, including reasonable attorneys fees and expenses, incurred by the Manager or either Co-Tenant in connection with the actual or proposed withdrawal of a Co-Tenant shall be paid or reimbursed by the withdrawing Co-Tenant upon any request therefor from the Manager and the other Co-Tenant.

7.1 In General. The Manager, at the direction of the Co-Tenants as specified in this Agreement, at all times shall do the following: (a) use reasonable efforts to cause the Shared Facilities to be operated and maintained in accordance with the Shared Facilities Contracts, the O&M Agreement, Prudent Industry Practices and any applicable Laws; (b) take any and all action as may be reasonably necessary to enforce and preserve warranty claims or other claims related to the Shared Facilities; (c) use reasonable efforts to oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority applicable to the Co-Tenants use, operation or ownership of the Shared Facilities and keep all Co-Tenants fully apprised as to the foregoing matters affecting the Shared Facilities; (d) use reasonable efforts to perform all regulatory reporting, auditing and other related matters (including with respect to any obligations imposed by NERC or FERC on the Shared Facilities) arising out of, or in connection with, the Shared Facilities; and (e) take such other actions as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing, unless in any such case, such action is not in the commercially reasonable interest of the Co-Tenants.
7.2 Specific Authority. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the Manager may take any of the following actions in the performance of its services, without obtaining the further approval from the Co-Tenants:
28 7.2.1. interface with each Co-Tenant with respect to day-to-day management, operations and maintenance of the Shared Facilities;
7.2.2. negotiate, enter into, execute, acknowledge or amend agreements relating to the management, use, operation, maintenance, capital improvements to, and repair of the Shared Facilities, in each case in accordance with the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget; provided, however, that (a) no such actions shall materially and adversely affect the rights or privileges of any of the Co-Tenants under this Agreement, or the use or operation of or access to the Shared Facilities by any of the Co-Tenants, or the availability of the Shared Facilities to any of the Co-Tenants, and (b) the Manager shall provide each Co-Tenant with copies of any such agreement or amendment promptly upon execution thereof;
7.2.3. pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Facilities, and maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained, in each case in accordance with the then-effective Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget;
7.2.4. procure insurance policies pursuant to Article 11; and
7.2.5. execute, acknowledge, and deliver any and all instruments and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent therewith.
7.3 Limitation on Authority. The Manager shall not, without the approval of both Co-Tenants:
7.3.1. create or cause to be created any Lien (other than Permitted Liens) on any of the Shared Facilities;
7.3.2. sell, assign, mortgage, encumber, convey or otherwise transfer all or any portion of the Undivided Interests held by either Co-Tenant, or any components of the Shared Facilities (other than as permitted under this Agreement);
7.3.3. borrow funds or otherwise incur indebtedness on behalf of a Co-Tenant;
7.3.4. agree to terminate, amend, or replace the O&M Agreement; consent to any assignment of Operators obligations under the O&M Agreement, or waive any obligation of Operator thereunder where such action would have a material adverse effect on the Shared Facilities or the Manager or any Co-Tenant.

29 7.5 Audit Rights. If any such inspection or audit discloses an error and that, as a result thereof, any overpayment or any underpayment has occurred hereunder, the amount thereof, together with interest at the Default Rate (except that any underpayment caused by the actions or inactions of Manager will not bear interest), shall be paid, within thirty (30) days after receipt of an invoice (with reasonable supporting detail) therefor, to the Co-Tenant to which it is owed by the Co-Tenant obligated therefor; provided, further, that a Co-Tenant shall be liable only for any amounts hereunder that relate to errors discovered and disclosed within the inspection and audit period provided for in this provision.
7.6 Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget. On or before November 30th of each year, the Manager shall provide each Co-Tenant with a draft of (i) the annual budget for the Shared Facilities for the immediately following calendar year and (ii) the annual operating plan setting forth the underlying assumptions and implementation plans for such budget (the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget). The Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget will include a separate operating budget and capital budget and will set forth, in reasonable detail, anticipated operations plans and costs, including forecasts of electricity production and corresponding usage of major commodities, repairs and capital improvements (including major maintenance and a cost/benefits analysis for proposed capital improvements), Scheduled Outages, routine maintenance and overhaul schedules, procurement (including equipment acquisitions and spare parts and consumable inventories indicating a breakdown of capital items and expense items), staffing, personnel and labor activities (including unit rates for labor and holidays to be observed), administrative activities, data regarding other work proposed to be undertaken by the Manager and regarding expected environmental performance, together with an itemized estimate of all Shared Expenses to be incurred in connection therewith. Items in the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget will be divided and identified as (a) target budget items and (b) non-target budget items, which are items over which the Manager has little or no control. Each Co-Tenant may submit any comments or questions to the Manager within thirty (30) days of receipt of the draft Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget. The Manager shall incorporate any comments received and shall provide a final Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget to the Co-Tenants by January 15th of the following year for approval by unanimous vote of the Co-Tenants. If, by the first day of any calendar year, the Co-Tenants and the Manager are unable to reach agreement concerning any portion of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget for such calendar year, such Dispute will be submitted for resolution in accordance with the Dispute resolution procedures set forth in Section 14.18. Pending the outcome of such Dispute resolution process and amendment of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget to reflect such outcome for purposes of the remainder of such calendar year, the portion of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget that is in Dispute will be resolved by using the portion of the Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget as proposed by the Manager for such disputed portion. The Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget may be amended during the year by unanimous vote of the Co-Tenants.
30 7.7 Emergencies. Any out-of-pocket costs reasonably incurred by the Manager in an Emergency shall be treated as Shared Expenses.

The Manager shall permit the Co-Tenants to access the Shared Facilities at reasonable times and during regular business hours for purposes of verifying the Managers operation of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the requirements of this Agreement or inspecting the Shared Facilities, provided that in each case the applicable Co-Tenant arranges any such inspection with Manager reasonably in advance thereof and complies with the safety requirements imposed by Manager. The Manager at all times will retain responsibility for performing its services as Manager in accordance with the requirements of this Agreement, regardless of whether or not the Co-Tenants have reviewed or inspected such services, plans, documentation or other acts or items.
7.10 Risk of Loss; Loss Events.
7.10.1. Risk of Loss. As between the Co-Tenants and Manager, the Co-Tenants (in proportion to their respective Percentage Interests) shall be responsible for the risk of loss to the Shared Facilities or any portion thereof during the term of this Agreement.
7.10.2. Loss Events. Upon the occurrence of a Loss Event, the Manager shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, prepare a written proposal (a Restoration Proposal) in consultation with the Co-Tenants to rebuild, repair, restore, or replace the portion of the Shared Facilities affected by such Loss Event, which Restoration Proposal shall contain, in appropriate detail, (a) a budget identifying all categories and approximate amounts reasonably anticipated to be incurred, (b) a progress and completion schedule and (c) a written plan, in each case, for the proposed rebuilding, repair, restoration, or replacement of the Shared Facilities. Notwithstanding the immediately preceding sentence, in the event of an Emergency or a Casualty Event requiring, in the Managers reasonable discretion, immediate or prompt action, the Manager may commence action to rebuild, repair, restore, or replace the applicable portion of the Shared Facilities pending preparation of the Restoration Proposal. The Manager, to the extent necessary or prudent, may
31 coordinate preparation of the Restoration Proposal with similar activity undertaken by or on behalf of any of the Co-Tenants arising out of the Loss Event in respect of Project Specific Assets. Any costs, expenses or other Liabilities associated with the preparation of the Restoration Proposal shall be Shared Expenses reimbursed by each Co-Tenant in proportion to its Percentage Interest as of the date of the Loss Event. Within 30 days after receipt of a Restoration Proposal from the Manager, each Co-Tenant shall notify the Manager and the other Co-Tenant in writing of whether it elects to participate in the rebuilding, repair, restoration, or replacement of the Shared Facilities. Any costs, expenses or other Liabilities associated with the rebuilding, repair, restoration, or replacement of the portion of the Shared Facilities affected by a Loss Event shall be Shared Expenses reimbursed by each Co-Tenant that has elected to participate in such activity, in proportion to its Percentage Interest. Any Co-Tenant that elects not to participate in the rebuilding, repair, restoration, or replacement of the Shared Facilities or that fails, within the thirty (30) day period specified above, to provide notice of its election, shall be deemed to have given a Withdrawal Notice as of the earlier of (i) the date of such election or (ii) the end of such thirty (30) day period.

The Manager shall have the right to change the Manager Representative at any time and from time to time by written notice to the Co-Tenants. For avoidance of doubt, Manager may appoint a representative of Operator to serve as the Manager Representative.

Throughout the term of this Agreement, the Manager shall perform its services as Manager and all other obligations under this Agreement in accordance with the Shared Facilities Contracts, the O&M Agreement, the applicable Annual Shared Facilities Operating Plan and Budget, Prudent Industry Practices, and all applicable Laws and Governmental Approvals. For avoidance of doubt, Manager may appoint Operator to perform services on behalf of Manager and otherwise to fulfill Managers obligations under this Agreement, but Manager shall remain liable for all obligations under this Agreement notwithstanding any such appointment of Operator.
7.13 Assignment of Warranties. The Manager shall be responsible for enforcing, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, all manufacturer, construction, and other warranties with respect to the Shared Facilities and any parts or materials associated therewith. The Co-Tenants and the Manager shall cooperate in the enforcement of the foregoing warranties, and to the extent possible, any Co-Tenant holding a warranty for a portion of the Shared Facilities shall assign such warranty to Manager for enforcement and collection, and any funds received in lieu of repair or replacement shall be used for repair or replacement of the affected Shared Facilities. Any excess warranty funds shall be distributed to the Co-Tenants in proportion to their Percentage Interest. Description of Battery Storage Project
A battery energy storage system (BESS) encompassing approximately 1.6 acres will be added to the existing well pad infrastructure maintained by Coso Geothermal Power Holdings, LLC and operated by Coso Operating Company LLC. The BESS will be located within the confines of Well Pad 23-19, which is within the fenced confines of the existing BLM-West geothermal power plant. The geothermal well field is on the BLM Lease in the Coso Known Geothermal Resources Area (KGRA) within the confines of Naval Air Weapons Station (NAWS) China Lake, in Inyo County, California. The BESS site is entirely located on a BLM Lease on withdrawn public lands, managed by the U.S. Navy. The BESS will deliver 25 megawatts (MW) and store up to 120 megawatt hours (MWh) of electricity for delivery into the local Southern California Energy (SCE) grid via the Inyokern Substation. The addition of the BESS to the well pads and power plant area will also require adding an underground 13.8 kilovolt (kV) distribution line, and overhead 13.8 kV distribution lines to connect the BESS to the BLM-West Substation. The distribution lines will connect into a new switchyard adjacent to an existing substation on disturbed land within the existing geothermal power plant boundary. Construction activities will occur over an 8- to 9-month period.
